This passage is generally found puzzling to a beginner on two accounts. Firstly, he is apt to fancy Dialectic synonymous with Logic, and to confound it with the formal Science os that name3 an error which the Com- mentary most likely to fall in his way is not unlikely to confirm. In explanation it may be observed: First, that Dialectic and Rhetoric are not formal Sciences, but material Arts. Their Logic is not a Loyica docens, treating of the general form of Reasoning, but a Loyica utem, treating of Reasoning as applied to a particular matter. That matter is furnished by the τόποι. Rhetoric and Dialectic do not merely lay down the forn] in which their reasonings ought to proceed, but likewise provide certain general principles of probability, froin which the matter of their major premises is to be drawn. They are not gained by exclusive observation of any one particular class of objects belonging to this or that art or faculty, but are indifferently applicable to all.
